DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
Habermas's engagement with Weber is one of the most sustained confrontations in
twentieth-century social theory. In The Theory of Communicative Action (1981),
Habermas devotes two major chapters to reconstructing and then radically revising
Weber's rationalization thesis. He accepts Weber's core insight that modernity
involves the systematic differentiation of value spheres (science, morality, art)
and that societal rationalization has produced both the disenchantment of worldviews
and the rise of bureaucratic-capitalist subsystems. But he argues that Weber's
diagnosis is imprisoned within what Habermas (following his critique of the
Frankfurt School's Dialectic of Enlightenment) calls "subject-centered" or
"philosophy of consciousness" reason: Weber identifies rationality exclusively with
purposive-rational (Zweckrational) action — the lone subject calculating means to
ends — and thereby cannot perceive the intersubjective, communicative dimension of
reason that is equally basic to modernity. The key consequences of this limitation,
as Habermas diagnoses them, are: (1) Weber's concept of rationality is
one-dimensional — it conflates formal-procedural and cognitive-instrumental
rationality, missing communicative rationality entirely; (2) Weber cannot generate
normative resources for immanent critique from within the tradition of modernity
itself, because his theory offers no standpoint from which purposive rationality's
pathological dominance could be criticized; (3) Weber's pessimistic diagnosis —
the "iron cage" and the "polar night of icy darkness" — becomes a dead-end because
his monological framework bars any recuperative potential in the rationalized
lifeworld; and (4) Weber's action-theory is methodologically anchored in a solo
actor who orients action toward subjective ends, thus missing the co-constitutive
role of communicative interaction. In The Philosophical Discourse of Modernity
(1985), Habermas deepens this critique by connecting Weber's subject-philosophy to
Nietzsche and the trajectory that leads to postmodernism, arguing that only the
paradigm-shift to communicative reason can escape the aporias of subject-centered
reason.

Countercritiques from Weberian scholars are equally important. Wolfgang Schluchter
defends the complexity of Weber's rationalization scheme (formal, substantive,
theoretical, practical types of rationality) and challenges Habermas's reading as
reductive. Lawrence Scaff argues that Habermas neglects Weber's tragic dimension
and his sophisticated analysis of culture, values, and political life. Stephen
Kalberg's typology of Weber's four types of rationality makes it difficult to
sustain Habermas's charge of one-dimensionality. Keith Breen's monograph "Under
Weber's Shadow" (2012) is the most sustained recent analysis, arguing that Habermas
moves beyond Weber's monological subjectivism through intersubjectivity but at the
cost of depoliticizing key arenas of human endeavor and underweighting the genuine
tragedy of value pluralism that Weber saw clearly.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain is central to the research idea, because Habermas's methodological and
theoretical departures from Weber directly shape his philosophy of history and
development: his claim that communicative rationality provides a normative telos
immanent in modernity (the "unfinished project") that Weber's purposive-rational
framework cannot generate is the hinge on which Habermas's theory of modernity
turns. The critical responses from Weberian scholars also illuminate what Habermas
gains and loses in his reconstruction, including the question of whether his more
optimistic reading of modernity adequately addresses the polytheism of values and
the tragic dimension of rationalization.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
Habermas's specific handling of Weber's methodology (ideal types, Verstehen,
value-freedom) as distinct from his sociology of rationalization has received
relatively little focused attention compared to the action-theory and rationalization
critiques. The connection between Habermas's critique of Weber's "subject
philosophy" and his theory of communicative evolution/developmental history is also
understudied.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
The synthesis should structure the Habermas-Weber confrontation around three axes:
(1) the "one-sidedness" charge and the communicative turn; (2) the normative deficit
critique and its implications for immanent critique; (3) Weberian countercritiques
challenging the fairness or completeness of Habermas's reading. Recent work by
Prasai (2024) and Breen (2012) can anchor the contemporary stakes.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Habermas's internal critique of Weber: 8 papers — Habermas argues Weber's
  subject-centered reason prevents adequate critique and emancipatory potential
- Weberian defenses/countercritiques: 5 papers — Schluchter, Scaff, Kalberg,
  Breen challenge Habermas's reading as reductive or distorting
- Synthesis and mediation: 2 papers — Dahms, Prasai trace the Weberian Marxist
  tradition and recent reconstructions
====================================================================
}

