  RELEVANCE: This essay offers a contemporary political theory perspective on the Habermas-Weber debate, focusing specifically on democratic theory rather than broader questions of modernity and rationalization. Salam's Weber-inspired critique of Habermasian deliberative democracy connects to current debates about populism, technocracy, and epistemic democracy. The argument that Habermas' proceduralism masks rather than addresses the autonomy of state officials and opinion leaders challenges the practical viability of discourse ethics in modern mass democracies.

